{{outdated|date=July 2016}} {{Use British English|date=March 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}} On 6 December 2007, '''Odyssey Moon''' was the first team to register for the [[Google Lunar X Prize]] competition,<ref name="space1"/> an event that hopes to rekindle the efforts of humans to return to the moon. The competition is referred to as "Moon 2.0" and is composed of other private organizations like Odyssey Moon Limited, the commercial lunar enterprise that makes up this team.<ref name ="space">{{Cite web|title=Odyssey Moon first off the mark for the Google Lunar X PRIZE|url=http://www.space.co.uk/Articles/20071209OdysseyMoon/tabid/99/Default.aspx|publisher=''space.co.uk''|accessdate=2008-02-06}}</ref> Each team will be competing for a $20 million first prize, a $5 million second prize, and additional $5 million in (potential) bonuses.<ref name ="xprize">{{Cite web|title=Odyssey Moon Announced as First Official Competitor in the Google Lunar X PRIZE|url=http://www.googlelunarxprize.org/|publisher=''googlelunarxprize.org''|accessdate=2008-02-06}}</ref> [[File:MCSB - LADEE.jpg|thumb|left|Odyssey Moon will utilize the basic design of this NASA hover test vehicle.<ref name="sfn">{{Cite web|title=Moon beckons commercial comeback for Beagle|author=Craig Covault|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/news/n0908/12beagle/|publisher=''Spaceflight Now''|year=2009|accessdate=2010-02-03}}</ref>]]
Odyssey Moon Limited is based on [[The Isle of Man]],<ref name="space"/> and is the design of [[Robert D. Richards]].<ref name="xprize"/> His goals include developing the first commercial enterprise that utilizes the energy and resources on the moon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reaching for the moon: Interview with Robert Richards|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/TECH/space/05/05/richards.interview/index.html#cnnSTCText|publisher=''[[CNN]]''|accessdate=2008-06-25 | date=2008-05-09}}</ref> To achieve this end, the team enlisted the part-time consultant services of [[Alan Stern]], NASA's former top-rank planetary scientist.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Former NASA chief Alan Stern joins Odyssey Moon|url=http://www.odysseymoon.com/PDF/Odyssey_Moon_Media_Release_-_Alan_Stern_18_June_2008.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010211509/http://odysseymoon.com/PDF/Odyssey_Moon_Media_Release_-_Alan_Stern_18_June_2008.pdf|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2008-10-10|publisher=''Odyssey Moon''|accessdate=2008-07-16}}</ref> On 22 September 2008, another veteran of NASA joined Odyssey Moon. [[Jay F. Honeycutt]] was named president and will be responsible for all programs and commercial launch operations. He brings a great deal of expertise in managing large scale engineering operations. His experience at NASA was diverse. He was director of the [[Kennedy Space Center]] for several years and was director of Shuttle Management and Operations for more than five years. Outside NASA, another part of his forty years of professional experience was as president of [[Lockheed Martin]] Space Operations from 1997-2004.<ref name="jay_pr">{{Cite web|title=Former NASA Kennedy Space Center Director Jay Honeycutt Announced As President of Odyssey Moon U.S. Operations|url=http://www.spaceref.com/news/viewpr.html?pid=26491|publisher=''spaceref.com''|accessdate=2008-09-22}}</ref>{{Update after|2010|11|13}}
The team's goals are to build and deploy a robotic lander that will deliver exploration as well as scientific payloads to the moon. The new lander/spacecraft has been dubbed "MoonOne (M-1)".<ref>{{Cite web|title=Private race to the moon (and money) takes off|author=Dave Mosher|author2=Anthony Duignan-Cabrera|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/23278871/page/2/|publisher=''[[Space.com]]''|accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref> These efforts have been contracted to [[MacDonald Dettwiler]], a Canadian corporation with a successful history of providing technical space solutions for several [[NASA]] projects including the [[Space Shuttle]] and the [[International Space Station]].<ref name="space"/>{{Update after|2010|11|13}}
[[The Planetary Society]], an international space interest group co-founded by [[Carl Sagan]], joined Odyssey Moon's efforts in 2007, specifically with public outreach and coordination between public and private organizations.<ref name="space1">{{cite web|title=Private Company Accepts Google Lunar X Prize Challenge|url=http://www.space.com/businesstechnology/071206-private-odyssey.html|author=Leonard David|year=2007|publisher=''[[Space.com]]''|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>
[[Colin Pillinger]], a scientist with a background in studying meteorites, led the [[European Space Agency]]'s failed [[Beagle 2]] Mars lander project in 2003. In 2009 he was in discussion with Odyssey Moon regarding the use of an identical version of Beagle's most powerful instrument on their lander.<ref name="sfn"/>{{Update after|2010|11|13}}
